'''Level 11.3''' is a sub-level between Levels [[Level 11|11]] and [[Level 12|12]] and a hotspot for wanderer traffic due to its various beneficial properties.

== '''Description''' ==
{{Blurimage|file=Level 11.3.jpg|caption=A photograph of several skyscrapers from '''Level 11.3''', one being a replica of the Empire State Building.}}
'''Level 11.3''', informally referred to as "The Skyscrape", presents itself as a set of incredibly tall skyscrapers. The buildings of this sub-level vary in architecture and design, with most following the 20th-century brutalist style, while others may follow more antiquated or modern styles. Some may even replicate existing skyscrapers from [[The Frontrooms]]<ref>Replicas of the Empire State Building, the Burj Khalifa, the Lakhta Center, and the Jeddah Tower have been found throughout this level.</ref>. The average height of these buildings is speculated to be around 8700 meters tall, though some have been reported to reach over 13000 meters. A few of the skyscrapers on this level feature architecture that defies the laws of physics and exhibits [[Phenomenon 14]].

The buildings of '''Level 11.3''' are interconnected by bridges, staircases, or even zip lines. These structures can be made of metal, glass, or concrete and exhibit abnormal resistance compared to their [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]] counterparts.

Each skyscraper is divided into several floors, all of which are completely pristine. Most upper floors are filled with large glass windows and are mostly empty, with the exception of some armchairs and vending machines selling common [[Object List|Backrooms Objects]] scattered throughout the rooms. These rooms are completely devoid of entities. A wanderer will typically appear on these floors after noclipping into this level. The roofs of these buildings can be reached by climbing the stairs connecting each floor to the highest one; the roofs have no safety nets, and it is not recommended to go there, as the strong winds at '''Level 11.3''' may push one out of the skyscraper. Some buildings have ladders on the roof that allow wanderers to climb down to the lower locations of '''Level 11.3'''. No one who's climbed down the ladder has ever returned.

The middle floors of the skyscrapers are far more detailed and complex, varying in size and layout depending on the building's architecture and floors' function, though they all share the characteristic of having much smaller, less prevalent windows than the upper floors. Some floors in this section may resemble restaurants, with a large number of chairs, tables, a kitchen, and self-replenishing sources of nutrition. Other floors may resemble storage rooms, with several shelves filled with resources. A few floors have been reported to feature hotel rooms with clean beds, a television connected to the Internet, and a freezer stocked with [[Object 1|Almond Water]]. One can occasionally find entities on the middle floors of '''Level 11.3'''<nowiki/>'s skyscrapers<ref>More commonly, in the storage rooms of the middle floors.</ref>; for this reason, it is important to bring proper equipment to these places.

{{Blurimage|file=Level 11.3.webp|caption=A skyscraper estimated to be 11000 meters tall in '''Level 11.3'''.}}

Not much is known about the lower floors of the skyscrapers aside from their distinct lack of light; this is due to the large number of entities inhabiting these rooms, which makes exploration impossible.

The only sounds present in '''Level 11.3''' are the wind and lounge music, which can occasionally be heard from an unknown source while inside hotel rooms and restaurants on the middle floors of the skyscrapers. These songs are usually taken from existing music from the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]], though some have reported hearing completely unrecognizable melodies. The music that plays inside this level is confirmed not to be a hallucination, as audio recordings do capture these songs.

After noclipping into '''Level 11.3''', a wanderer's sanity will gradually increase over the course of a week; they will become happier and start feeling more energetic than usual. While this effect is mostly beneficial, it may encourage adventurous wanderers to explore this level's depths, which can put their health at risk. After some months in '''Level 11.3''', the wanderer will become lethargic and more relaxed. Noclipping out of '''Level 11.3''' will cause these effects to gradually decrease in intensity over the course of a month.

'''Level 11.3'''<nowiki/>'s sky does not follow a circadian day-night cycle, staying sunlit at all times and covered in a thick fog that impairs the eyesight of the wanderer 200 meters ahead. Rarely, rain may fall from the sky, even though few clouds will be visible.

The air pressure in '''Level 11.3''' remains constant at all times and is not affected by altitude, allowing wanderers to breathe normally. However, it is important to note that the wind blows significantly stronger at higher altitudes. Another anomaly that occurs in the skybox of this level causes clouds to constantly fluctuate in height; in some cases, clouds have been reported to descend 2000 meters into the ground or 4000 meters up into the air. This phenomenon also affects the wind speeds at '''Level 11.3''', with the wind blowing much stronger during periods when clouds are lower in the sky.

It is scientifically proven that this level is not affected by [[Phenomenon 15]], as few encounters between wanderers here have been documented. However, it is extremely difficult to find others in '''Level 11.3''' due to its gargantuan scale, which can separate wanderers tens or even hundreds of kilometers away from each other.

{{Blurimage|file=Level 11.3.jpeg|caption=Photograph of wanderer Ogden Løtenessier inside of one of the upper floors of a skyscraper in '''Level 11.3'''.}}

== '''Entities''' ==
There are various documented entities inside '''Level 11.3''', all restricted to the middle and lower floors of each skyscraper.

[[Entity 9|Facelings]], [[Entity 190|Plastic Worms]], [[Entity 190#Wimpworms|Wimpworms]], and [[Entity 57|Chatterers]] can occasionally be seen on the middle floors of the skyscrapers that resemble restaurants and hotel rooms. Middle floors resembling storage rooms are more packed with entities, with the confirmed presence of [[Entity 83|Cone Spiders]], [[Entity 4|Deathmoths]] and [[Entity 72|Foams]] inhabiting them.

The lower floors of the buildings are so densely populated with entities that exploration is deemed impossible. [[Entity 3|Smilers]], [[Entity 36|Lighters]], [[Entity 30|Peekers]], [[Entity 62|Aranea Membri]], and [[Entity 82|Growlers]] are common sights on these floors.

== '''Bases, Communities & Outposts''' ==
While '''Level 11.3''' can easily sustain many communities with its large amount of resources and psychological benefits, the immense scale of this level makes contact between wanderers extremely rare and difficult. However, the [[M.E.G.|M.E.G]] has stated that it will establish an outpost here once enough personnel and wanderers meet each other. 

== '''Entrances & Exits''' ==

=== '''Entrances''' ===

* Noclipping into an abnormally tall building in [[Level 11]] will lead one here.
* Accidental noclipping inside [[Level 4.3]] will take one here.
* Finding a building in [[Level 385]] bearing a strong resemblance to the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]]' skyscrapers and noclipping into it will lead to '''Level 11.3'''.

=== '''Exits''' ===

* Noclipping into a vending machine on the upper floors of a skyscraper will lead one to [[Level 334]].
* Finding an extremely rare waterlogged skyscraper will take one to [[Level 11.11]].
* Hotel rooms on the middle floors of skyscrapers may lead one to [[Level 5.1]] or in rare cases, If the hotel seems destroyed, it could lead to [[Level 319]].
* Staying too long inside one of the bridges connecting 2 skyscrapers may transition the landscape to [[Level 4.11]].
* In the upper floors of the buildings, an extensively rare out-of-place elevator transfers one to [[Absolute Infinity of Unknown|Absolute Infinity of the Unknown]].
